\begin_layout Abstract
We study a recently proposed by Ijjas and Steinhardt particular realization
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Ijjas:2016tpn"

\end_inset

 of the cosmological bounce scenario.
 First, we reveal the exact construction of the Lagrangian used in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Ijjas:2016tpn"

\end_inset

.
 This explicit construction allowed us to study other cosmological solutions
 in this theory.
 In particular we found solutions with superluminal speed of sound and discuss
 the consequences of this feature for a possible UV-completion.
 Further, following the originally constructed background history, we evaluated
 the tensor and scalar spectra during the bouncing phase characterized by
 the violation of the null energy condition.
 We found that the change of the speed of sound is the cause of the dominance
 of the tensor power spectrum over the scalar part through most of the bounce.
 Moreover, we observe that none of the spectra evaluated across the bouncing
 phase is scale invariant.
 In addition to this, we present our results for particle production by
 showing the evolution of the occupation number of scalar fluctuations through
 the bounce.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Introduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since 2011 it is well known that scalar-tensor theories with Kinetic Gravity
 Braiding (which are also called first two terms of Horndeski or simple
 generalized Galileons) allow for 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Qiu:2011cy,Easson:2011zy"

\end_inset

 a classical bouncing evolution manifestly free from ghost and gradient
 instabilities around the bounce.
 The possibility of the bounce in such systems was briefly mentioned in
 Moreover, in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Easson:2011zy"

\end_inset

 it was demonstrated that one can easily construct spatially flat bouncing
 universes, without ghosts and gradient instabilities and with bouncing
 solutions of a non-vanishing measure.
 Moreover, in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Easson:2011zy"

\end_inset

 it was demonstrated that there is a continuum of such minimally coupled
 theories of the type of Kinetic Gravity Braiding.
 This Ref.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Easson:2011zy"

\end_inset

 provided inequalities on two free functions of kinetic term present in
 Lagrangian of the theory, which are sufficient to guaranty a healthy bounce.
 It was also showed that this setup also works in a presence (in fact unavoidabl
e) of the normal matter - like radiation etc.
 In one of examples ("Hot G-Bounce") it was even showed that such a bouncing
 universes can smoothly transit to the radiation dominated stage.
 In this work it was also discussed that there is always a singularity (either
 in the gravitational or acoustic metric).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Model and main equations 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In 2016, Ijjas and Steinhardt proposed a particular realization 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Ijjas:2016tpn"

\end_inset

 of the cosmological bounce scenario in a particular subclass of these theories.
 For convenience we denote this realization as 
\emph on
IS-bounce
\emph default
.
 The IS-bounce was claimed to be free from ghost and gradient instabilities
 and free from superluminal propagation of perturbations.
 The explicit case of the IS-bounce uses a class of Kinetic Gravity Braiding
 theories with explicitly strongly 
\emph on
broken
\emph default
 shift-symmetry 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi\rightarrow\phi+c$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
S=\frac{1}{2}\int d^{4}x\,\sqrt{-g}\left(k\left(\phi\right)\left(\partial\phi\right)^{2}+\frac{1}{2}q\left(\phi\right)\left(\partial\phi\right)^{4}+\left(\partial\phi\right)^{2}\Box\phi\right)\,,\label{eq:IS_Lagrangian}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left(\partial\phi\right)^{2}\equiv g^{\mu\nu}\partial_{\mu}\phi\partial_{\nu}\phi\equiv2X\,,\qquad\Box\phi\equiv g^{\mu\nu}\nabla_{\mu}\nabla_{\nu}\phi\,,
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla_{\mu}$
\end_inset

 is the usual Levi-Civita connection 
\lang english

\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Further we use: the standard notation 
\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{-g}\equiv\sqrt{-\text{det}g_{\mu\nu}}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{\mu\nu}$
\end_inset

 is the metric, the signature convention 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(+,-,-,-\right)$
\end_inset

 (contrary to 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Ijjas:2016tpn"

\end_inset

), and the units 
\begin_inset Formula $c=\hbar=1$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{\text{Pl}}=\left(8\pi G_{\text{N}}\right)^{-1/2}=1$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset


\lang american
.
 The scalar field is supposed to be minimally coupled to gravity.
 Hence the theory is defined by two free functions 
\begin_inset Formula $k\left(\phi\right)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $q\left(\phi\right)$
\end_inset

.
 In notation of 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Deffayet:2010qz"

\end_inset

 we have
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
At the beginning the authors of 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Ijjas:2016tpn"

\end_inset

 also used 
\begin_inset Formula $G\left(X,\phi\right)=b\left(\phi\right)X$
\end_inset

, however this additional free function 
\begin_inset Formula $b\left(\phi\right)$
\end_inset

 can be eliminated by a simple field-redefinition.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
K\left(X,\phi\right)=k\left(\phi\right)X+q\left(\phi\right)X^{2}\,,\qquad G\left(X,\phi\right)=X\,.\label{eq:KGB_identifiaction}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

This identification allows us to directly use all necessary formulas derived
 in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Deffayet:2010qz"

\end_inset

 for arbitrary 
\begin_inset Formula $K\left(X,\phi\right)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $G\left(X,\phi\right)$
\end_inset

, see also 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Kobayashi:2010cm"

\end_inset

.
 In particular the pressure is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
P=kX+qX^{2}-2X\ddot{\phi}\text{ ,}
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
J=\dot{\phi}\left(k+2qX+3\dot{\phi}H\right)\text{ ,}
\]

\end_inset

the energy density 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\varepsilon=\dot{\phi}J-kX-qX^{2}
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\dot{H}=X\ddot{\phi}-\frac{1}{2}\dot{\phi}J\text{ ,}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The quadratic action for curvature perturbations 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{R}$
\end_inset

 reads
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Note that 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Ijjas:2016tpn"

\end_inset

 does not use the canonical normalization with 
\begin_inset Formula $1/2$
\end_inset

 in front of the action.
 Hence our coefficients 
\begin_inset Formula $A\left(t\right)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $B\left(t\right)$
\end_inset

 are twice larger then those in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Ijjas:2016tpn"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
S_{2}=\frac{1}{2}\int dt\,d^{3}x\,a^{3}\left(A\left(t\right)\dot{\mathcal{R}}^{2}-\frac{B\left(t\right)}{a^{2}}\left(\partial_{i}\mathcal{R}\right)^{2}\right)\,.\label{eq:quadratic_action_scalars}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The formula for the normalization of the kinetic term is given by (A.9) page
 36, 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Deffayet:2010qz"

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
A=\frac{2XD}{\left(H-\dot{\phi}XG_{,X}\right)^{2}}\,,\label{eq:Our_Normalization}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where the quantity 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
D=K_{,X}+2XK_{,XX}-2G_{,\phi}-2XG_{,X\phi}+6\dot{\phi}H\left(G_{,X}+XG_{,XX}\right)+6X^{2}G_{,X}^{2}\,,\label{eq:D_for_ghosts}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

determines (
\begin_inset Formula $D>0$
\end_inset

) whether the perturbations are free of ghosts.
 The sound speed is given by the formula (A.11) page 36, 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Deffayet:2010qz"

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
c_{s}^{2}=\frac{B\left(t\right)}{A\left(t\right)}=\frac{\dot{\phi}XG_{,X}\left(H-\dot{\phi}XG_{,X}\right)-\partial_{t}\left(H-\dot{\phi}XG_{,X}\right)}{XD}\,,\label{eq:speed_of_sound}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where we assumed that the field 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 is the only source of energy-momentum.
 From this expression we can write 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{1}{2}B\left(t\right)=\frac{\dot{\phi}XG_{,X}\left(H-\dot{\phi}XG_{,X}\right)-\partial_{t}\left(H-\dot{\phi}XG_{,X}\right)}{\left(H-\dot{\phi}XG_{,X}\right)^{2}}\text{ .}\label{eq:B_kgb}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Hence it is natural to introduce a convenient variable
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\gamma=H-\dot{\phi}XG_{,X}\text{ ,}\label{eq:gamma}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

in terms of which 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{1}{2}B\left(t\right)=\frac{d}{dt}\gamma^{-1}+H\gamma^{-1}-1\text{ .}\label{eq:B_general}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The expression for 
\begin_inset Formula $B\left(t\right)$
\end_inset

 was written in this elegant form in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Ijjas:2016tpn"

\end_inset

 for a particular choice 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:KGB_identifiaction"

\end_inset

 of functions 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

.
 However, before that this variable 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:gamma"

\end_inset

 was used in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Libanov:2016kfc"

\end_inset

, see equation (2.6) page 4.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For the Lagrangian given by 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:KGB_identifiaction"

\end_inset

 one obtains 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\gamma\left(t\right)=H-\dot{\phi}X\,,\label{eq:Gamma_IS_Lagrangian}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

so that 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:B_kgb"

\end_inset

 (or 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:B_general"

\end_inset

) yields
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
B=\frac{2X\left(k+2qX+4H\dot{\phi}+2\ddot{\phi}-2X^{2}\right)}{\left(H-\dot{\phi}X\right)^{2}}\,.\label{eq:B_IS}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

While the general expression 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:D_for_ghosts"

\end_inset

 gives 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
D=k+6Xq+6\dot{\phi}H+6X^{2}\,,\label{eq:D_IS}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

 and consequently 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:Our_Normalization"

\end_inset

 reads 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
A=\frac{2X\left(k+6qX+6\dot{\phi}H+6X^{2}\right)}{\left(H-\dot{\phi}X\right)^{2}}\,.\label{eq:Normalization}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Inverse method, finding the theory 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The authors of IS-bounce pustulated a particular fairly simple time-dependence
 of the Hubble parameter 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
H\left(t\right)=H_{0}\,t\,\exp\left(-F\left(t-t_{*}\right)^{2}\right)\,,\label{eq:Hubble_IS}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{0}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{*}$
\end_inset

 are constants, and proposed an 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

inverse method
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 to find free functions 
\begin_inset Formula $k\left(\phi\right)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $q\left(\phi\right)$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:IS_Lagrangian"

\end_inset

 which can realize this cosmological evolution.
  
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The key observation of the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

inverse method
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 proposed in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Ijjas:2016tpn"

\end_inset

 is that one can can also independently postulate 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma\left(t\right)$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:B_general"

\end_inset

.
 The IS-bounce postulates 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\gamma=\gamma_{0}\exp\left(3\theta t\right)+H\left(t\right)\,,\label{eq:Gamma _IS}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma_{0}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 are additional constants with respect to already introduced 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{0}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{*}$
\end_inset

.
 From 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:Gamma_IS_Lagrangian"

\end_inset

 one can obtain 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\phi\left(t\right)=\phi_{0}+\int_{t_{0}}^{t}dt'\left(2\left(H-\gamma\right)\right)^{1/3}\,,
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi\left(t_{0}\right)=\phi_{0}$
\end_inset

.
 It is convenient to chose this initial value as 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{0}=\left(-2\gamma_{0}/\theta\right)^{1/3}\exp\left(3t_{0}\right),$
\end_inset

 so that the particular solution postulated in IS-bounce is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\phi\left(t\right)=\left(\frac{-2\gamma_{0}}{\theta^{3}}\right)^{1/3}\exp\left(\theta t\right)\,.\label{eq:phi_solution}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

For the later it is suitable to denote 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\phi_{\star}=\left(\frac{-2\gamma_{0}}{\theta^{3}}\right)^{1/3}\,,
\]

\end_inset

as a characteristic field range, so that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
t=\frac{1}{\theta}\text{log}\left(\phi/\phi_{\star}\right)\,.\label{eq:time_IS_solution}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Using the substitutions 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:Hubble_IS"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:Gamma _IS"

\end_inset

 one obtains the functions 
\begin_inset Formula $k\left(\phi\right)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $q\left(\phi\right)$
\end_inset

 as functions of time on the particular solution 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:phi_solution"

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
k\left(t\right)=-\frac{2\left(2\dot{H}+3H^{2}+\dot{\gamma}+3H\gamma\right)}{\left(2\left(H-\gamma\right)\right)^{2/3}}\,,\label{eq:k(t)}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

and 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
q\left(t\right)=\frac{4\left(2\dot{H}+\dot{\gamma}+9H\gamma\right)}{3\left(2\left(H-\gamma\right)\right)^{4/3}}\,.\label{eq:q(t)}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

For the later it is convenient to introduce functions 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
W\left(\phi\right)=\exp\left[\frac{F}{\theta^{2}}\left(\log\left(\frac{\phi}{\phi_{\star}}\right)-\theta t_{*}\right){}^{2}\right]\,,\label{eq:W_IS}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

and 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\Omega\left(\phi\right)=W\left(\phi\right)\theta^{3}\left(\theta\phi\right)^{3}+H_{0}\left[\log\left(\frac{\phi}{\phi_{\star}}\right)\left(4F\left[\log\left(\frac{\phi}{\phi_{\star}}\right)-\theta t_{*}\right]+2\theta\left(\theta\phi\right)^{3}\right)-2\theta^{2}\right]\,,\label{eq:Omega_IS}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

in terms of which the defining functions are 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
k(\phi)=-\frac{12H_{0}^{2}\log^{2}\left(\phi/\phi_{\star}\right)-3W\left(\phi\right)\left[\Omega\left(\phi\right)-H_{0}\theta\left(\theta\phi\right)^{3}\log\left(\phi/\phi_{\star}\right)\right]}{W^{2}\left(\phi\right)\theta^{2}\left(\theta\phi\right){}^{2}}\,,\label{eq:k(phi)}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

and 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
q\left(\phi\right)=\frac{12H_{0}^{2}\log^{2}\left(\phi/\phi_{\star}\right)-2W\left(\phi\right)\left[\Omega\left(\phi\right)+H_{0}\theta\left(\theta\phi\right)^{3}\log\left(\phi/\phi_{\star}\right)\right]}{W^{2}\left(\phi\right)\theta^{2}\left(\theta\phi\right){}^{4}}\,.\label{eq:q(phi)}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

These expressions defining the theory which should be related to the origins
 of the universe neither look well-motivated nor natural from any point
 of view.
 This is the prize for the chosen simple exact solution 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:Hubble_IS"

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
