\begin_layout Subsection
Setting up the equations of motion and initial conditions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The field dynamics of these fluctuations is described by the Lagrangian
 in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:IS_Lagrangian"

\end_inset

 expanded in second order of perturbations written in Fourier space, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{L}_{\mathbf{k}}^{(2)}=\frac{a^{3}A(t)}{2}\left(\left|\dot{\mathcal{R}_{\mathbf{k}}}\right|^{2}-\frac{k^{2}c_{s}^{2}}{a^{2}}\left|\mathcal{R}_{\mathbf{k}}\right|^{2}\right)+\frac{a^{3}}{4}\sum_{p=+,\times}\left[\left|\dot{h}_{\mathbf{k}}^{p}\right|^{2}-\frac{k^{2}}{a^{2}}\left|h_{\mathbf{k}}^{p}\right|^{2}\right].\label{eq:IS_second_order}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Where tensor modes are also included apart from the scalar curvature shown
 in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:Scalar_curv"

\end_inset

 and the index 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 is a placeholder for any of the polarization modes, conventionally denoted
 by 
\begin_inset Formula $(+)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $(\times)$
\end_inset

.
 In this case, the speed of sound follows from its previous definitions
 and 
\begin_inset Formula $A(t)$
\end_inset

 is the same as in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:Normalization"

\end_inset

.
 We derive the equations of motion after varying the action built from the
 previous expression with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{R}_{\mathbf{k}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $h_{\mathbf{k}}^{p}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
 & {\displaystyle {\ddot{\mathcal{R}}_{\mathbf{k}}+\frac{d\ln(a^{3}A(t))}{dt}\dot{\mathcal{R}}_{\mathbf{k}}+\frac{k^{2}c_{s}^{2}}{a^{2}}\mathcal{R}_{\mathbf{k}}=0,}}\\
 & {\displaystyle {\ddot{h}_{\mathbf{k}}^{p}+3H\dot{h}_{\mathbf{k}}^{p}+\frac{k^{2}}{a^{2}}h_{\mathbf{k}}^{p}=0.}}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

With the help of the auxiliary variables 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{R}_{\mathbf{k}}\equiv a^{-3/2}A(t)^{-1/2}\mathcal{S}_{\mathbf{k}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $h_{\mathbf{k}}^{p}\equiv\sqrt{{2}}a^{-3/2}\mathcal{T}_{\mathbf{k}}^{p}$
\end_inset

 it is possible to write these equations in the form of two decoupled simple
 harmonic oscillators, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
 & {\displaystyle {\ddot{\mathcal{S}}_{\mathbf{k}}+\omega_{\mathcal{S}}^{2}\mathcal{S}_{\mathbf{k}}=0,}\label{eq:IS_{e}qmov_{s}calar}}\\
 & {\displaystyle {\ddot{\mathcal{T}}_{\mathbf{k}}^{p}+\omega_{\mathcal{T}}^{2}\mathcal{T}_{\mathbf{k}}^{p}=0,}\label{eq:IS_{e}qmov_{t}ensor}}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

where the functions 
\begin_inset Formula $z\equiv a^{3/2}A^{1/2}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y\equiv a^{3/2}$
\end_inset

 are useful in order to define the natural frequencies for both oscillators
 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{\mathcal{S}}^{2}\equiv k^{2}c_{s}^{2}/a^{2}-\ddot{z}/z$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{\mathcal{T}}^{2}\equiv k^{2}/a^{2}-\ddot{y}/y$
\end_inset

.
 For simplicity, we will evolve these auxiliary variables instead of the
 original scalar and tensor modes; however it is not a problem to determine
 the dynamics of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{R}_{\mathbf{k}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $h_{\mathbf{k}}^{p}$
\end_inset

 after inverting the definitions of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{S}_{\mathbf{k}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{T}_{\mathbf{k}}^{p}$
\end_inset

.
 Initial conditions can be determined by instantaneous energy minimization
 after diagonalizing the Hamiltonian of an harmonic oscillator with a time-depen
dent frequency in a fixed instant of time, even when it is well-known that
 this selection criteria is not unique.
 The promotion of these solutions to field operators is given by, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\hat{\mathcal{S}}_{\mathbf{k}}=\mathcal{S}_{\mathbf{k}}\hat{a}_{\mathbf{k}}+\mathcal{S}_{\mathbf{k}}^{*}\hat{a}_{\mathbf{-k}}^{\dagger}~;~\hat{\mathcal{T}}_{\mathbf{k}}^{p}=\mathcal{T}_{\mathbf{k}}^{p}\hat{b}_{\mathbf{k}}+(\mathcal{T}_{\mathbf{k}}^{p})^{*}\hat{b}_{\mathbf{-k}}^{\dagger},
\]

\end_inset

and is consistent with the reality condition for all the fluctuation modes.
 
\begin_inset Formula $(\hat{a}_{\mathbf{k}},\hat{a}_{\mathbf{k}}^{\dagger})$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $(\hat{b}_{\mathbf{k}},\hat{b}_{\mathbf{k}}^{\dagger})$
\end_inset

 are the creation and annihilation operators for scalar and tensor perturbations.
 Any generic solution to 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:IS_eqmov_scalar"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:IS_eqmov_tensor"

\end_inset

 can be written as a function of two real modes 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{S}_{\mathbf{k}}=\mathcal{S}_{\mathbf{k}}^{(1)}+i\mathcal{S}_{\mathbf{k}}^{(2)}$
\end_inset

.
 From the standard commutation relations for the ladder operators 
\begin_inset Formula $[\hat{a}_{\mathbf{k}},\hat{a}_{\mathbf{k}}^{\dagger}]=1$
\end_inset

 and the equal-time commutator 
\begin_inset Formula $[\hat{\mathcal{S}}_{\mathbf{k}},\dot{\hat{\mathcal{S}}}_{\mathbf{k}}]=i$
\end_inset

, we can show that the Wronskian of these real modes satisfies, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathcal{S}_{\mathbf{k}}^{(1)}\dot{\mathcal{S}}_{\mathbf{k}}^{(2)}-\mathcal{S}_{\mathbf{k}}^{(2)}\dot{\mathcal{S}}_{\mathbf{k}}^{(1)}=\frac{1}{2},
\]

\end_inset

at every instant of time, in agreement with the canonical commutations relations.
 The same procedure follows to write conservation of the Wronskian for the
 tensor modes.
 Hence, it is possible to write the canonically normalized initial conditions
 for all the modes involved, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
 & {\displaystyle {\dot{\mathcal{S}}^{(1)}(t_{0})=0~;~\mathcal{S}^{(1)}(t_{0})=\frac{1}{\sqrt{2\omega_{\mathcal{S}}(t_{0})}}},\nonumber}\\
 & {\displaystyle {\dot{\mathcal{S}}^{(2)}(t_{0})=\sqrt{\frac{\omega_{\mathcal{S}}(t_{0})}{2}}~;~\mathcal{S}^{(2)}(t_{0})=0},\label{eq:IS_{i}nit_{S}}}\\
 & {\displaystyle {(\dot{\mathcal{T}}^{p})^{(1)}(t_{0})=0~;~(\mathcal{T}^{p})^{(1)}(t_{0})=\frac{1}{\sqrt{2\omega_{\mathcal{T}}(t_{0})}}},\nonumber}\\
 & {\displaystyle {(\dot{\mathcal{T}}^{p})^{(2)}(t_{0})=\sqrt{\frac{\omega_{\mathcal{T}}(t_{0})}{2}}}~;~(\mathcal{T}^{p})^{(2)}(t_{0})=0,\label{eq:IS_{i}nit_{T}}}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

in an analogous way than the standard prescription for the Bunch-Davies
 vacuum.
 Notice that even in the limit of high 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

, it is possible to observe that 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{s}^{2}(t)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $a(t)$
\end_inset

 make the scalar initial conditions not invariant under time translations.
 Our objective with this choice of initial conditions is the instantaneous
 minimization of the energy per 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

-mode for 
\emph on
only
\emph default
 positive values of 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{\mathcal{T}}^{2}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{\mathcal{S}}^{2}$
\end_inset

 before the bounce.
 In this way, we will compare the state of the system at any posterior instant
 of time with the zero-point energy state at 
\begin_inset Formula $t=t_{0}$
\end_inset

 of a time-dependent harmonic oscillator.
 This would be a suitable (but not unique) way to define equations of motion
 while setting initial conditions that minimize the energy of the system
 before the bounce.
 Notice that the evaluation of the expressions in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:IS_init_S"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:IS_init_T"

\end_inset

 at all the posterior instants of time should never be treated as solutions
 to the equations of motion.
 Nevertheless, there is another way to rephrase the system that increases
 the performance of a numerical computation.
 For instance, let us rewrite the eikonal separation 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{S}_{\mathbf{k}}=L_{\mathcal{S}}\exp(i\Theta_{\mathcal{S}})$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $L_{\mathcal{S}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\Theta_{\mathcal{S}}$
\end_inset

 are real.
 Then we replace this expression in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:IS_eqmov_scalar"

\end_inset

 obtaining two equations after separating the real and imaginary parts,
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
 & \ddot{L}_{\mathcal{S}}+(\omega_{\mathcal{S}}^{2}-\dot{\Theta}_{\mathcal{S}}^{2})L_{\mathcal{S}}=0~~\mathrm{(Real\:part)},\nonumber \\
 & \ddot{\Theta}_{\mathcal{S}}+2\frac{\dot{L}_{\mathcal{S}}}{L_{\mathcal{S}}}\dot{\Theta}_{\mathcal{S}}=0~~\mathrm{(Imaginary\:part)},\label{eq:IS_phase_S}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:IS_phase_S"

\end_inset

 has a simple analytic solution given by 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{\Theta}_{\mathcal{S}}(t)=L_{\mathcal{S}}^{2}(t_{0})\dot{\Theta}_{\mathcal{S}}(t_{0})/L_{\mathcal{S}}^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 Hence, the only equation to solve for the scalar modes is, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\ddot{L}_{\mathcal{S}}+\left[\omega_{\mathcal{S}}^{2}-L_{\mathcal{S}}^{4}(t_{0})\frac{\dot{\Theta}_{\mathcal{S}}^{2}(t_{0})}{L_{\mathcal{S}}^{4}}\right]L_{\mathcal{S}}=0.\label{eq:IS_amp_S}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The same idea can be straightforwardly applied for the tensor modes after
 replacing all the tensor components of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{T}_{\mathbf{k}}^{p}$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $L_{\mathcal{T}}^{p}\exp(i\Theta_{\mathcal{T}})$
\end_inset

.
 Assuming the same contribution from all polarizations, this will lead us
 to an analogous result for the phase velocity 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{\Theta}_{\mathcal{T}}(t)$
\end_inset

 and the equation of motion for the amplitudes differ from 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:IS_amp_S"

\end_inset

 only by considering 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{\mathcal{T}}^{2}$
\end_inset

 instead of 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{\mathcal{S}}^{2}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\ddot{L}_{\mathcal{T}}^{p}+\left[\omega_{\mathcal{T}}^{2}-(L_{\mathcal{T}}^{p})^{4}(t_{0})\frac{\dot{\Theta}_{\mathcal{T}}^{2}(t_{0})}{(L_{\mathcal{T}}^{p})^{4}}\right]L_{\mathcal{T}}^{p}=0.\label{eq:IS_amp_T}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

It is important to remember that the power spectrum only depends on the
 amplitudes of the original modes, which can found at all times by, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
|\mathcal{R}_{\mathbf{k}}|=\frac{|\mathcal{S}_{\mathbf{k}}|}{a^{3/2}A^{1/2}}=\frac{L_{\mathcal{S}}}{a^{3/2}A^{1/2}}\:,\:|h_{\mathbf{k}}^{p}|=\frac{\sqrt{{2}}|\mathcal{T}_{\mathbf{k}}^{p}|}{a^{3/2}}=\frac{\sqrt{{2}}L_{\mathcal{T}}^{p}}{a^{3/2}}.\label{eq:IS_amplitudes}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Initial conditions in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:IS_init_S"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:IS_init_T"

\end_inset

 are reproduced after evaluating 
\begin_inset Formula $\Theta_{\mathcal{T}}(t_{0})=0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\Theta_{\mathcal{S}}(t_{0})=0$
\end_inset

, similarily 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{L}_{\mathcal{T}}^{p}(t_{0})=0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{L}_{\mathcal{S}}(t_{0})=0$
\end_inset

.
 The amplitudes of the modes and the phase derivatives are the only initial
 conditions with non-trivial values, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
 & {L}_{\mathcal{S}}(t_{0})=\frac{1}{\sqrt{2\omega_{\mathcal{S}}(t_{0})}}~~;~~\dot{\Theta}_{\mathcal{S}}(t_{0})=\omega_{\mathcal{S}}(t_{0}),\label{eq:IS_real_ICs_scalar}\\
 & {L}_{\mathcal{T}}^{p}(t_{0})=\frac{1}{\sqrt{2\omega_{\mathcal{T}}(t_{0})}}~~;~~\dot{\Theta}_{\mathcal{T}}(t_{0})=\omega_{\mathcal{T}}(t_{0}),\label{eq:IS_real_ICs_tensor}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

where the effective frequency of the harmonic oscillators in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:IS_amp_S"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:IS_amp_T"

\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $t=t_{0}$
\end_inset

 is exactly zero for the scalar and tensor modes regardless of the values
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

.
 This procedure describes the single field realization of the separation
 technique of fast and slow components shown in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Ghersi:2016gee"

\end_inset

.
 Our construction relies heavily in the positivity of 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{\mathcal{T}}^{2}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{\mathcal{S}}^{2}$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $t=t_{0}$
\end_inset

, for that reason the initial instant of time where the mode evolution starts
 needs to be chosen properly in order to avoid diverging initial conditions.
 Both functions are positive in the range of very high values of 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

, therefore we evaluated both effective frequencies in Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:w_eff_ST"

\end_inset

 in the low 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 limit.
 Henceforth, we choose 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{0}=-90\:t_{\mathrm{Pl}}$
\end_inset

 to be the initial instant of time where the evolution of perturbations
 begin.
 Moreover, it is also (approximately) the first moment where both 
\begin_inset Formula $A(t)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{s}^{2}$
\end_inset

 are finite and positive, thus the system of scalar and tensor fluctuations
 evolves in a time domain where it is free from ghost and gradient instabilities.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Evolution of the mode amplitudes and length scales
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The definitions of the effective oscillation frequencies for the scalar
 curvature 
\begin_inset Formula $(\omega_{\mathcal{S}}^{2})$
\end_inset

 and primordial tensor 
\begin_inset Formula $(\omega_{\mathcal{T}}^{2})$
\end_inset

 modes shows that only the scalar fluctuations propagate with sound speed
 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{s}$
\end_inset

.
 It is relevant, therefore, to compare the evolution of different physical
 length scales as these propagate from sub-horizon scales.
 Let us define the two physical scales with respect to a given comoving
 wavelength 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{\mathrm{com}}$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
 & {\displaystyle {\lambda_{\mathrm{phys}}^{\mathcal{S}}=\frac{a\lambda_{\mathrm{com}}}{c_{s}},}\label{lambda_{S}}}\\
 & {\displaystyle {\lambda_{\mathrm{phys}}^{\mathcal{T}}=a\lambda_{\mathrm{com}},}\label{lambda_{T}}}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

which can be identified as the corresponding wavelength part from the definition
s of 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{\mathcal{S}}^{2}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{\mathcal{T}}^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 We now evaluate the time derivative of the logarithmic versions of these
 two quantities, obtaining 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
 & {\displaystyle {\frac{d\ln\lambda_{\mathrm{phys}}^{\mathcal{S}}}{dt}=H-\frac{1}{2}\left(\frac{\dot{B}}{B}-\frac{\dot{A}}{A}\right),}\label{lambda_{d}ot_{S}}}\\
 & {\displaystyle {\frac{d\ln\lambda_{\mathrm{phys}}^{\mathcal{T}}}{dt}=H.}\label{lambda_{d}ot_{S}}}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
From these expressions, we notice that none of these derivatives depends
 on the specific values of the evolving scalar or tensor wavelengths.
 From the form of 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 suggested for the IS-bounce in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:Hubble_IS"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:Gamma _IS"

\end_inset

 along with the construction of 
\begin_inset Formula $A(t)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $B(t)$
\end_inset

 described in equations (14) and (17) in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Ijjas:2016tpn"

\end_inset

, it is possible to compare the evolution of all the physical length scales
 
\begin_inset Formula $(\ell_{\mathrm{phys}})$
\end_inset

 including the sound and particle horizon: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
{\displaystyle {s_{\mathrm{H}}=\int\frac{c_{s}(t)dt}{a(t)}~;~p_{\mathrm{H}}=\int\frac{dt}{a(t)},}}
\]

\end_inset

through the bouncing phase.
 In Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:scalar_lengths"

\end_inset

, as an example, we observe the evolution of the sound horizon and three
 sub-horizon physical wavelengths (
