\begin_layout Subsection
Evolution of the scalar and tensor power spectrum and particle production
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this subsection, we evaluate the scale dependence and other specific
 features of the power spectrum of scalar and tensor perturbations through
 the IS bouncing trajectory from the choice of instantaneous minimal energy
 initial conditions set in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:IS_real_ICs_scalar"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:IS_real_ICs_tensor"

\end_inset

 right before the bounce.
 In addition to this, we also calculate the evolution of the occupation
 number of scalar and tensor fluctuations, observing that some of the features
 of the spectra are due to particle production.
 The power spectra of primordial scalar and tensor fluctuations follow from
 the typical definition given by, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
P_{\mathcal{R}}(k)=\frac{k^{3}}{2\pi^{2}}|\mathcal{R}_{\mathbf{k}}(t)|^{2}~~,~~P_{h}(k)=\frac{k^{3}}{2\pi^{2}}\sum_{p=+,\times}|h_{\mathbf{k}}^{p}(t)|^{2},\label{eq:IS_spectrum}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where the time evolution of the amplitudes 
\begin_inset Formula $|\mathcal{R}_{\mathbf{k}}(t)|^{2}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $|h_{\mathbf{k}}^{p}(t)|^{2}$
\end_inset

 follows from the numerical solutions for 
\begin_inset Formula $L_{\mathcal{S}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $L_{\mathcal{T}}$
\end_inset

 described in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:IS_amp_S"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:IS_amp_T"

\end_inset

 respectively.
 The calculations for particle production become much simpler to evaluate
 after we rephrase the equations of motion as in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:IS_eqmov_scalar"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:IS_eqmov_tensor"

\end_inset

.
 We define the occupation number as, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\langle n_{\mathbf{k}}(t)\rangle=\frac{a^{4}A(t)}{2kc_{s}}\left[|\dot{\mathcal{R}}_{\mathbf{k}}|^{2}+\frac{k^{2}c_{s}^{2}}{a^{2}}|\mathcal{R}_{\mathbf{k}}|^{2}\right]-\frac{1}{2},\label{eq:IS_number}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
for the production of scalar fluctuations.
 The tensor counterpart is defined in an analog way.
 In contrast with the definitions in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Barnaby:2010ke"

\end_inset

, the last expression is not built from the time-dependent harmonic oscillators
 in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:IS_eqmov_scalar"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:IS_eqmov_tensor"

\end_inset

 in order to not make these quantities divergent in the limit where 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{\mathcal{S}}^{2}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{\mathcal{T}}^{2}$
\end_inset

 vanish.
 In Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:sp_amps"

\end_inset

, we evaluate the dependence of the amplitudes with 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 in four different instants of time.
 We evaluated the scalar and tensor power spectra in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:IS_spectrum"

\end_inset

, showing that none of the spectra is scale invariant.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We must remark that the amplitude of the tensor modes dominates over the
 scalar amplitudes through most of the bouncing phase, as we can see in
 figures 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:sp_0"

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:sp_1"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:sp_2"

